            "specs": "Technology|Gyroscopic rotor ball\nDisplay|Optional (costs more for counter version)\nTarget Areas|Wrists, forearms, grip\nBest For|Grip strength, rehabilitation\nScore|⭐⭐⭐⭐ 7.8/10",
            "summary": "<p>The Powerball has a legitimate following — and a legitimate function. The gyroscopic rotor does create real resistance, and regular use will strengthen your wrists and forearms. It's the oldest and most proven technology in this category.</p><p>The problem is that it's essentially a grip-strength tool that happens to engage your forearms. It doesn't engage the upper arm. It doesn't target the tricep area women consistently ask me about — the underside of the arm that waves when you wave. And at higher RPMs, some women in my test group found it uncomfortable to hold.</p><p>The other issue: without a display, you have no measurable goal. You spin it, you feel it work, and then... you put it down. The 360° Trainer's LCD counter turned out to be more important than I initially thought — it's the difference between \"exercising\" and \"training.\"</p>",
            "how_steps": "",
            "metrics": "",
